dsko","England":"Anglie, United Kingdom","London, England":"Londýn, Anglie"},"da":{"1470–1535":"1470–1535","1477–Female":"1477–Afdød","1511–1552":"1511–1552","1535":"1535","1524":"1524","1523":"1523","before 1511":"før 1511","1511":"1511","1477":"1477","1520":"1520","1497":"1497","1552":"1552","1495":"1495","about 1511":"omkring 1511","1470":"1470","Högsjö, Sodermanland, Sweden":"Högsjö, Södermanland, Sverige","England":"England, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England"},"nl":{"1470–1535":"1470–1535","1477–Female":"1477–Overleden","1511–1552":"1511–1552","1535":"1535","1524":"1524","1523":"1523","before 1511":"vóór 1511","1511":"1511","1477":"1477","1520":"1520","1497":"1497","1552":"1552","1495":"1495","about 1511":"circa 1511","1470":"1470","Högsjö, Sodermanland, Sweden":"Högsjö, Södermanland, Zweden","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","London, England":"London, England"},"en":{"1470–1535":"1470–1535","1477–Female":"1477–Deceased","1511–1552":"1511–1552","1535":"1535","1524":"1524","1523":"1523","before 1511":"before 1511","1511":"1511","1477":"1477","1520":"1520","1497":"1497","1552":"1552","1495":"1495","about 1511":"about 1511","1470":"1470","Högsjö, Sodermanland, Sweden":"Högsjö, Södermanland, Sweden","England":"England, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Anderson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: patronymic from the personal name <i>Ander(s)</i>, a northern Middle English form of   Andrew  , + <i>son</i> ‘son’. The frequency of the surname in Scotland is attributable, at least in part, to the fact that Saint Andrew is the patron saint of Scotland, so the personal name has long enjoyed great popularity there. Legend has it that the saint's relics were taken to Scotland in the 4th century by a certain Saint Regulus. In North America, this surname has absorbed many cognate or like-sounding surnames in other languages, notably Scandinavian (see 3 and 4 below), but also Ukrainian <b>Andreychenko</b> etc.","German: patronymic from the personal name   Anders  , hence a cognate of 1 above.","Americanized form (and a less common Swedish variant) of Swedish   Andersson  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Andrew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the usual vernacular English form (recorded from the 13th century onward) of the New Testament Greek personal name   Andreas  . In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Czech <b>Ondřej</b> (see   Ondrey  ) and Albanian   Ndreu  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives (see examples at   Andrews  ).","History: The surname Andrew was first brought to North America from England by Robert Andrew (died 1668), who settled in Boxford, MA."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1357051,"age":25,"year":"1495","julianDay":2267098,"description":"Russians forces invade Sweden.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702078,"age":25,"year":"1495","toYear":"1497","julianDay":2267098,"title":"The Russo-Swedish War","description":"While in an alliance with Grand Prince Ivan III of Moscow, King Hans of Denmark and Norway invaded Sweden and was declared King of Sweden.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russo-Swedish_War_(1495%E2%80%931497)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Swedish War","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702079,"age":50,"year":"1520","julianDay":2276228,"title":"The Stockholm Bloodbath","description":"A mass execution of Swedish nobles by Danish king Christian II is known as the Stockholm Bloodbath. Christian II invaded Sweden in 1519 and took hold of Stockholm in September 1520. Over 80 nobles were executed for heresy on November 8 and 9. The outrage from the executions led to the Swedish removal of support of the Kalmar Union.","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/Stockholm-Bloodbath","urlTitle":"Britannica - Stockholm Bloodbath","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702080,"age":53,"year":"1523","julianDay":2277324,"title":"Swedish War of Liberation","description":"The Swedish War of Liberation was a civil war led by nobleman Gustav Vasa. As Christian II heard of the rebellion, he confronted Vasa's men, who won the battle at Brunbacks Ferry. Christian II was defeated by the Swedes in Stockholm and a truce was agreed upon. Vasa was given as a hostage as a show of good faith until the treaty was signed. The Danish King did not keep his word and Vasa was held as a prisoner for two years until his escape. A bounty was placed on Vasa's head. Vasa worked to inspire many to join his cause and lived under disguise until the Danes surrendered in 1525.","url":"https://www.sweden.org.za/swedish-monarchy-gustav-vasa.html","urlTitle":"Sweden.org - Swedish Monarchy Gustav Vasa","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702082,"age":54,"year":"1524","julianDay":2277689,"title":"Treaty of Malmo","description":"The Treaty of Malmo was signed on September 1, 1524, which ended the Swedish War of Liberation and the independence of Sweden was recognized by Denmark and Norway.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Henry Anderson was born in 1470, in England. He married Jane before 1511, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1535, in Högsjö, Södermanland, Sweden, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1470–1535":"1470–1535","1477–Female":"1477–Surnud","1511–1552":"1511–1552","1535":"1535","1524":"1524","1523":"1523","before 1511":"enne 1511","1511":"1511","1477":"1477","1520":"1520","1497":"1497","1552":"1552","1495":"1495","about 1511":"umbes 1511","1470":"1470","Högsjö, Sodermanland, Sweden":"Högsjö, Södermanland, Rootsi","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England"},"fi":{"1470–1535":"1470–1535","1477–Female":"1477–Kuollut","1511–1552":"1511–1552","1535":"1535","1524":"1524","1523":"1523","before 1511":"ennen vuotta 1511","1511":"1511","1477":"1477","1520":"1520","1497":"1497","1552":"1552","1495":"1495","about 1511":"noin 1511","1470":"1470","Högsjö, Sodermanland, Sweden":"Högsjö, Södermanland, Ruotsi","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London, England":"London, England"},"fr":{"1470–1535":"1470–1535","1477–Female":"1477–Décédée","1511–1552":"1511–1552","1535":"1535","1524":"1524","1523":"1523","before 1511":"avant 1511","1511":"1511","1477":"1477","1520":"1520","1497":"1497","1552":"1552","1495":"1495","about 1511":"environ 1511","1470":"1470","Högsjö, Sodermanland, Sweden":"Högsjö, Södermanland, Suède","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","London, England":"Londres, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Sir Henry Anderson est né en 1470, à Angleterre. Il a épousé Jane avant 1511, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1535, à Högsjö, Södermanland, Suède, à l’âge de 65 ans."},"de":{"1470–1535":"1470–1535","1477–Female":"1477–Verstorben","1511–1552":"1511–1552","1535":"1535","1524":"1524","1523":"1523","before 1511":"vor 1511","1511":"1511","1477":"1477","1520":"1520","1497":"1497","1552":"1552","1495":"1495","about 1511":"um 1511","1470":"1470","Högsjö, Sodermanland, Sw